ze-mQVIC|date=2011|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-101-51514-3}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|voy=Roman Empire}}\n{{Library resources box |onlinebooks=yes}}\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/schools/romans Romans for Children], a BBC website on ancient Rome for children at primary-school level.\n* [https://darmc.harvard.edu/ The Digital Atlas of Roman and Medieval Civilizations]\n* [http://tacitus.nu/historical-atlas/rome.htm Historical Atlas] showing the expansion of the Roman Empire.\n* [http://roman-empire.net/ Roman-Empire.net], learning resources and re-enactments\n* [http://www.wdl.org/en/item/11745/ The Historical Theater in the Year 400 AD, in Which Both Romans and Barbarians Resided Side by Side in the Eastern Part of the Roman Empire]\n\n{{Ancient Rome topics |autocollapse}}\n{{Roman history by territory}}\n{{Territories with limited Roman Empire occupation & presence}}\n{{Empires}}\n{{Former monarchies Italian peninsula}}\n{{Ancient Syria and Mesopotamia}}\n{{History of Europe}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Empire|Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Ancient Italian history]]\n[[Category:Former countries on the Italian Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Former countries in Asia]]\n[[Category:Countries in ancient Africa]]\n[[Category:Superpowers]]\n[[Category:20s BC establishments in the Roman Empire|*]]\n[[Category:27 BC establishments]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in the 1st century BC]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in the 5th century]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1453]]\n[[Category:476 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:470s disestablishments]]\n[[Category:5th-century disestablishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:History of the Mediterranean]]\n[[Category:Former empires in Europe]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n", "name_user": "Primergrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Empire"}
{"title_page": "Aasim Sajjad Akhtar", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name =Aasim Sajjad Akhtar  \n| native_name = \u0639\u0627\u0635\u0645 \u0633\u062c\u0627\u062f \u0627\u062e\u062a\u0631 \n| nationality = Pakistani\n| alma_mater = [[SOAS, University of London]]<br>[[Yale University]]<br>[[Northwestern University]]\n| occupation = Associate Professor at [[Quaid-i-Azam University]], [[Islamabad]], [[Pakistan]]\n| known for = Former President, [[Awami Workers Party]] Punjab\n}}\n\n'''Aasim Sajjad Akhtar''' is a left-wing politician, academic and columnist based in [[Pakistan]]. He served as the president of the [[Awami Workers Party]]'s [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] Executive Committee till January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1094272|title=AWP body elected|last=|first=|date=20 March 2016|work=|newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|access-date=29 August 2016|via=}}</ref> Akhtar is associate professor of political economy at [[Quaid-i-Azam University]], Islamabad, [[Pakistan]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nAkhtar did his bachelor of Arts in Economics with Honours in 1997 from [[Northwestern University]], Evanston, IL, USA.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Northwestern University (Evanston |title=Annual commencement / Northwestern University. |url=https://archive.org/stream/annualcommenceme1997nort/annualcommenceme1997nort_djvu.txt |publisher=Evanston, Ill. : The University |date=1997}}</ref> He got his  master's degree in economics in 1999 from [[Yale University]], New Haven, CT, USA.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lancaster |first1=John |title=Pakistan's Modern Feudal Lords |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2003/04/08/pakistans-modern-feudal-lords/45b45d57-d74a-4b73-8098-1bdc9490c255/ |website=Washington Post |date=8 April 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nips.edu.pk/cv/aasim.pdf|title=Aasim Sajjad CV|last=|first=|date=2016-08-29|website=National Institute of Pakistan Studies|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Akhtar completed his PhD in 2008 from [[SOAS, University of London]] at the South Asia Institute, where his thesis was titled ''The Overdeveloping State: The Politics of Common Sense in Pakistan, 1971-2007''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/south-asia-institute/research/completed-phd-thesis/completed-phd-thesis-2007-2008.html|title=Completed PhD Thesis 2007-2008|last=|first=|date=|website=SOAS South Asia Institute|publisher=|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAkhtar is serving as associate professor of political economy at [[Quaid-i-Azam University]]'s National Institute of Pakistan Studies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nips.edu.pk/index/?p=90|title=Faculty \u2013 NIPS|website=nips.edu.pk|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> and has previously taught at the [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bgsmcs.fu-berlin.de/en/dates/lecture_2016_akhtar.html|title=Aasim Sajjad Akhtar: \"The Symbiotic Relationship Between 'Counter-Terrorism' and Neoliberal Development: The Case of the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC)\"|date=2016-04-11|website=www.bgsmcs.fu-berlin.de|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Political struggle==\nIn November 2007, he was arrested in [[Lahore]] with seventy other civil society activists for participating in an anti-government meeting held at the [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]] during the [[Pakistani state of emergency, 2007]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/274531/students|title=Students' rare show against emergency|last=|first=|date=2007-11-06|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lumsreview.com/2007/11/emergency-rule-turns-ugly.html|title=LUMS Review - Emergency Rule Turns Ugly|last=|first=|date=2007-11-04|website=LUMS Review|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917030311/http://www.lumsreview.com/2007/11/emergency-rule-turns-ugly.html|archive-date=2016-09-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nAkhtar was a coordinator of the People's Rights Movement, a left-wing confederation of working-class movements in Pakistan. In February 2010, PRM merged with the National Workers Party and the [[Communist Mazdoor Kissan Party]] to form the Workers Party Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/892286/salvation-of-masses-lies-in-changing-status-quo|title=Salvation of masses lies in changing status quo|last=|first=|date=2010-02-27|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> In 2012, the Workers Party Pakistan merged with other Left-wing parties to form the [[Awami Workers Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/761037/three-leftist-parties-to-merge-2|title=Three leftist parties to merge|last=|first=|date=2012-11-02|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> Akhtar is a strong supporter of Okara's peasant movement.<ref>{{cite news |title=The long drawn struggle {{!}} Encore {{!}} thenews.com.pk |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/tns/detail/560837-long-drawn-peasants-struggle |work=www.thenews.com.pk |date=May 1, 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Publications and Articles==\nAkhtar also writes a weekly column for the [[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] newspaper,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/authors/3/aasim-sajjad-akhtar|title=News stories for Aasim Sajjad Akhtar|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> he also wrote in [[Monthly Review]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Asia |first1=Akhtar |title=The China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor |url=https://monthlyreview.org/2018/06/01/the-china-pakistan-economic-corridor/ |website=Monthly Review |date=1 June 2018}}</ref> [[New Internationalist]],<ref>{{cite web |title=The democracy killers |url=https://newint.org/columns/essays/2002/09/01/democracy-killers/ |website=New Internationalist |language=en |date=2 September 2002}}</ref> Tanqeed,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aasim |first1=Akhtar |title=Failed State Or Fragmented Hegemony |url=http://www.tanqeed.org/2014/07/failed-state-or-fragmented-hegemony/}}</ref> and [[The Straits Times]].<ref>{{cite news |title='Normal' must look different after the crisis |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/normal-must-look-different-after-the-crisis |work=The Straits Times |date=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He has published many research articles as a researcher and academic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aasim Sajjad |url=http://www.nips.edu.pk/cv/aasim.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2019.23: Aasim Sajjad Akhtar, When a Movement Stops Moving: The Okara Peasant Struggle Twenty Years On |url=https://criticalasianstudies.org/commentary/2019/11/19/201923-aasim-sajjad-ahktar-when-a-movement-stops-moving-the-okara-peasant-struggle-twenty-years-on |website=CAS}}</ref> He has published a book named \"The Politics of Common Sense\" which describes the evolution of structure of power in [[Pakistan]] over the past four decades.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Akhtar |first1=Aasim Sajjad |title=The Politics of Common Sense: State, Society and Culture in Pakistan |journal=Cambridge Core |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/politics-of-common-sense/A7F6BAFF8DD214B1516187C810DE96D6# |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Politics of Common Sense: Everyday life in contemporary Pakistan {{!}} SOAS University of London |url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/south-asia-institute/events/seminars/09feb2018-the-politics-of-common-sense-everyday-life-in-contemporary-pakistan.html |website=www.soas.ac.uk |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Marxists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani academics]]\n[[Category:Pakistani writers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani columnists]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Quaid-i-Azam University faculty]]\n[[Category:Lahore University of Management Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:Awami Workers Party politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name =Aasim Sajjad Akhtar  \n| native_name = \u0639\u0627\u0635\u0645 \u0633\u062c\u0627\u062f \u0627\u062e\u062a\u0631 \n| nationality = Pakistani\n| alma_mater = [[SOAS, University of London]]<br>[[Yale University]]<br>[[Northwestern University]]\n| occupation = Associate Professor at [[Quaid-i-Azam University]], [[Islamabad]], [[Pakistan]]\n| known for = Former President, [[Awami Workers Party]] Punjab\n}}\n\n'''Aasim Sajjad Akhtar''' is a left-wing politician, academic and columnist based in [[Pakistan]]. He served as the president of the [[Awami Workers Party]]'s [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] Executive Committee till January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1094272|title=AWP body elected|last=|first=|date=20 March 2016|work=|newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|access-date=29 August 2016|via=}}</ref> Akhtar is associate professor of political economy at [[Quaid-i-Azam University]], Islamabad, [[Pakistan]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nAkhtar did his bachelor of Arts in Economics with Honours in 1997 from [[Northwestern University]], Evanston, IL, USA.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Northwestern University (Evanston |title=Annual commencement / Northwestern University. |url=https://archive.org/stream/annualcommenceme1997nort/annualcommenceme1997nort_djvu.txt |publisher=Evanston, Ill. : The University |date=1997}}</ref> He got his  master's degree in economics in 1999 from [[Yale University]], New Haven, CT, USA.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lancaster |first1=John |title=Pakistan's Modern Feudal Lords |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2003/04/08/pakistans-modern-feudal-lords/45b45d57-d74a-4b73-8098-1bdc9490c255/ |website=Washington Post |date=8 April 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nips.edu.pk/cv/aasim.pdf|title=Aasim Sajjad CV|last=|first=|date=2016-08-29|website=National Institute of Pakistan Studies|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Akhtar completed his PhD in 2008 from [[SOAS, University of London]] at the South Asia Institute, where his thesis was titled ''The Overdeveloping State: The Politics of Common Sense in Pakistan, 1971-2007''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/south-asia-institute/research/completed-phd-thesis/completed-phd-thesis-2007-2008.html|title=Completed PhD Thesis 2007-2008|last=|first=|date=|website=SOAS South Asia Institute|publisher=|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAkhtar is serving as associate professor of political economy at [[Quaid-i-Azam University]]'s National Institute of Pakistan Studies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nips.edu.pk/index/?p=90|title=Faculty \u2013 NIPS|website=nips.edu.pk|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> and has previously taught at the [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bgsmcs.fu-berlin.de/en/dates/lecture_2016_akhtar.html|title=Aasim Sajjad Akhtar: \"The Symbiotic Relationship Between 'Counter-Terrorism' and Neoliberal Development: The Case of the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC)\"|date=2016-04-11|website=www.bgsmcs.fu-berlin.de|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Political struggle==\nIn November 2007, he was arrested in [[Lahore]] with seventy other civil society activists for participating in an anti-government meeting held at the [[Human Rights Commission of Pakistan]] during the [[Pakistani state of emergency, 2007]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/274531/students|title=Students' rare show against emergency|last=|first=|date=2007-11-06|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lumsreview.com/2007/11/emergency-rule-turns-ugly.html|title=LUMS Review - Emergency Rule Turns Ugly|last=|first=|date=2007-11-04|website=LUMS Review|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917030311/http://www.lumsreview.com/2007/11/emergency-rule-turns-ugly.html|archive-date=2016-09-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nAkhtar was a coordinator of the People's Rights Movement, a left-wing confederation of working-class movements in Pakistan. In February 2010, PRM merged with the National Workers Party and the [[Communist Mazdoor Kissan Party]] to form the Workers Party Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/892286/salvation-of-masses-lies-in-changing-status-quo|title=Salvation of masses lies in changing status quo|last=|first=|date=2010-02-27|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> In 2012, the Workers Party Pakistan merged with other Left-wing parties to form the [[Awami Workers Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/761037/three-leftist-parties-to-merge-2|title=Three leftist parties to merge|last=|first=|date=2012-11-02|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> Akhtar is a strong supporter of Okara's peasant movement.<ref>{{cite news |title=The long drawn struggle {{!}} Encore {{!}} thenews.com.pk |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/tns/detail/560837-long-drawn-peasants-struggle |work=www.thenews.com.pk |date=May 1, 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Publications and Articles==\nAkhtar also writes a weekly column for the [[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] newspaper<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/authors/3/aasim-sajjad-akhtar|title=News stories for Aasim Sajjad Akhtar|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref>, he also wrote in [[Monthly Review]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Asia |first1=Akhtar |title=The China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor |url=https://monthlyreview.org/2018/06/01/the-china-pakistan-economic-corridor/ |website=Monthly Review |date=1 June 2018}}</ref>, [[New Internationalist]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The democracy killers |url=https://newint.org/columns/essays/2002/09/01/democracy-killers/ |website=New Internationalist |language=en |date=2 September 2002}}</ref>, Tanqeed,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aasim |first1=Akhtar |title=Failed State Or Fragmented Hegemony |url=http://www.tanqeed.org/2014/07/failed-state-or-fragmented-hegemony/}}</ref> and [[The Straits Times]]<ref>{{cite news |title='Normal' must look different after the crisis |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/normal-must-look-different-after-the-crisis |work=The Straits Times |date=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>. He has published many research articles as a researcher and academic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aasim Sajjad |url=http://www.nips.edu.pk/cv/aasim.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2019.23: Aasim Sajjad Akhtar, When a Movement Stops Moving: The Okara Peasant Struggle Twenty Years On |url=https://criticalasianstudies.org/commentary/2019/11/19/201923-aasim-sajjad-ahktar-when-a-movement-stops-moving-the-okara-peasant-struggle-twenty-years-on |website=CAS}}</ref> He has published a book named \"The Politics of Common Sense\" which describes the evolution of structure of power in [[Pakistan]] over the past four decades.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Akhtar |first1=Aasim Sajjad |title=The Politics of Common Sense: State, Society and Culture in Pakistan |journal=Cambridge Core |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/politics-of-common-sense/A7F6BAFF8DD214B1516187C810DE96D6# |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Politics of Common Sense: Everyday life in contemporary Pakistan {{!}} SOAS University of London |url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/south-asia-institute/events/seminars/09feb2018-the-politics-of-common-sense-everyday-life-in-contemporary-pakistan.html |website=www.soas.ac.uk |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Marxists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani academics]]\n[[Category:Pakistani writers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani columnists]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Quaid-i-Azam University faculty]]\n[[Category:Lahore Unive