{"title_page": "Aart van der Leeuw", "text_new": "[[File:Aart van der Leeuw.jpg|thumb|right|Aart van der Leeuw, 1899; photo by Carel Adama van Scheltema.]]\n'''Aart van der Leeuw''' (23 June 1876 \u2013 17 April 1931) was a Dutch writer of prose fiction and poetry. His reputation rests mostly on two novels, ''Ik en mijn speelman'' (1927) and ''De kleine Rudolf'' (1930).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2_JLL32RzrkC&pg=PA221|title=Columbia Dictionary of Modern European Literature|editor1-first=Jean Albert|editor1-last=B\u00e9d\u00e9|editor2-first=William Benbow|editor2-last=Edgerton|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1980|isbn=9780231037174|chapter=Dutch literature|pages=218\u201322}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAart van der Leeuw was born in [[Delft|Hof van Delft]] into a family of notable merchants. He had a strong bond with his mother, whose storytelling was very influential on him; later he read her his stories and poems. His years in elementary school were sad, apparently, and he later wrote about them in ''Kinderland'' (1914).<ref name=wage/> He attended the [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] in Delft, but he was a dreamer as a child who suffered in the harsh school environment where he was ridiculed. He had little interest in his studies (except for Dutch and history), and on top of that he had health problems, with his eyes and ears, which would plague him throughout his life. All this contributed to his graduating only at age 22, in 1898. He began publishing prose and poetry in his high school years (in the student magazines ''Vox Gymnasii'' and ''Nuntius Gymnasorium''\u2014in the latter he published verse inspired by [[Willem Kloos]]<ref name=wage>{{cite book|url=http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/bwn1880-2000/lemmata/bwn3/leeuw|chapter=\nLeeuw, Aart van der (1876-1931)|title= Biografisch Woordenboek van Nederland|volume=3|location=Den Haag|year=1989|first=H. A.|last=Wage}}</ref>), and read voraciously; the [[Tachtigers]] influenced him greatly, and he became a neo-Romantic of sorts. In addition, he got more critical of his family's Protestantism, but while he would become anti-church, he never became irreligious. In this time period he became friends with [[Carel Adama van Scheltema]] and with painter [[Jan Vogelaar]], who soon became a mentor to Van der Leeuw.<ref name=schipper/>\n\nHe studied law at the [[Universiteit van Amsterdam]] for practical purposes; his parents' financial situation was a concern to him, and law offered good social prospects. This proved motivation enough, and he graduated on time, in 1902, and then worked briefly at the city archives of Delft.<ref name=schipper/> In 1903 he started as ''chef de bureau''<ref name=wage/> at a life insurance company in [[Dordrecht]]. That same year he married his school friend Antonia Johanna Kipp; they had become engaged in 1899. Their marriage remained childless. She is present in many of his early poems and was much interested in mysticism and spirituality; she is credited with shifting Van der Leeuw from skepticism to religiosity,<ref name=schipper/> because of her non-dogmatic though Christian-inflected beliefs.<ref name=wage/>\n\nVan der Leeuw hated his job. He had agreed to take the accountancy exam and had to take classes for that; combined with the full work day he had little time left for creative work. In March 1907 he resigned his position, on his doctor's advice, for health reasons, but this turned out to be a blessing in disguise: now he was free to pursue his calling. On top of that, his wife's father died, shortly followed by her mother, and he and his wife moved to [[Voorburg]], where he could devote himself to playing the violin, reading, and writing. They lived there until his death at age 54.<ref name=schipper>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]]|accessdate=2 January 2019|url=https://www.digibron.nl/search/detail/012e9d1b05d4aa4e283fc4b2/aart-van-der-leeuw-bescheiden-speelman|language=nl|date=16 April 1981|title= Aart van der Leeuw, bescheiden speelman: Neo-romanticus was lichamelijk zwak, maar geestelijk sterk|first=J.|last=Schipper}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1931 he fell ill with [[pneumonia]] and [[pleurisy]], and never recovered. He died on 17 April, and was buried in Voorburg, with a modest ceremony. A family member read his poem \"Mijn vaders tuinen\" at the gravesite.<ref name=schipper/>\n\n== Work==\nThe novella ''Sint-Veit'' was his literary debut; published in 1908 in [[Albert Verwey]]'s magazine ''De Beweging'', it had been written years before, in Dordrecht. He published also in ''[[De Gids]]'' and ''[[De Nieuwe Gids]]'', but was less interested in the naturalist writers than he was in those of a more symbolist quality. Van der Leeuw began publishing poetry in 1909 and until 1926 published four collections. He also published three collections of short stories, four prose fiction books, critical prose, and some translations. Very much isolated in Voorburg and loath to mingle in the literary world, his friend Van Schendel helped him prepare a number of his books for publication, including ''Liederen en Balladen'' (1910), ''Kinderland'' (1913), and ''Herscheppingen'' (1916). He traveled abroad only when his friends gifted him a trip to Italy for his 50th birthday, a trip he credited with prompting him to write ''Ik en mijn speelman'', a typically neo-Romanticist book that thematizes the relationship between beauty and reality (influenced, Van der Leeuw said, by 17th-c spiritual writer and mystic [[Thomas Traherne]]) and chooses beauty over reality. In his next book, ''De kleine Rudolf'' (1930), there is an attempt to reconcile dream and reality, and now reality is accepted, with romanticism being sought in life, not outside of it. In 1928 he was awarded the [[Lucy B. en C.W. van der Hoogtprijs|C.W. van der Hoogtprijs]] by the [[Maatschappij der Nederlandse Letterkunde]] for ''Het aardsche paradijs'' (1927).<ref name=schipper/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Sint Veit'' (1908)\n* ''Liederen en balladen'' (1911)\n* ''Kinderland'' (1914)\n* ''Herscheppingen'' (1916)\n* ''Sint-Veit en andere vertellingen'' (1919)\n* ''De mythe van een jeugd'' (1921)\n* ''Opvluchten'' (1922)\n* ''De gezegenden'' (1923)\n* ''Vluchtige begroetingen'' (1925)\n* ''De zwerftochten van Odysseus'' (1926)\n* ''Het aardsche paradijs'' (1927)\n* ''Ik en mijn speelman'' (1927)\n* ''De kleine Rudolf'' (1930)\n* ''De opdracht'' (1930)\n* ''Verspreid proza'', nagelaten (1932)\n* ''Die van hun leven vertelden'' (1934)\n* ''Vertellingen'' (1935)\n* ''Momenten van schoonheid en bezinning'' (1947)\n* ''Verzamelde gedichten'' (1950)\n* ''De briefwisseling tussen P.N. van Eyck en Aart van der Leeuw'', bezorgd door Piet Delen (1973)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dutch writers]]\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Aart van der Leeuw.jpg|thumb|right|Aart van der Leeuw, 1899; photo by Carel Adama van Scheltema.]]\n'''Aart van der Leeuw''' (23 June 1876 \u2013 17 April 1931) was a Dutch writer of prose fiction and poetry. His reputation rests mostly on two novels, ''Ik en mijn speelman'' (1927) and ''De kleine Rudolf'' (1930).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2_JLL32RzrkC&pg=PA221|title=Columbia Dictionary of Modern European Literature|editor1-first=Jean Albert|editor1-last=B\u00e9d\u00e9|editor2-first=William Benbow|editor2-last=Edgerton|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1980|isbn=9780231037174|chapter=Dutch literature|pages=218-22}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAart van der Leeuw was born in [[Delft|Hof van Delft]] into a family of notable merchants. He had a strong bond with his mother, whose storytelling was very influential on him; later he read her his stories and poems. His years in elementary school were sad, apparently, and he later wrote about them in ''Kinderland'' (1914).<ref name=wage/> He attended the [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] in Delft, but he was a dreamer as a child who suffered in the harsh school environment where he was ridiculed. He had little interest in his studies (except for Dutch and history), and on top of that he had health problems, with his eyes and ears, which would plague him throughout his life. All this contributed to his graduating only at age 22, in 1898. He began publishing prose and poetry in his high school years (in the student magazines ''Vox Gymnasii'' and ''Nuntius Gymnasorium''--in the latter he published verse inspired by [[Willem Kloos]]<ref name=wage>{{cite book|url=http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/bwn1880-2000/lemmata/bwn3/leeuw|chapter=\nLeeuw, Aart van der (1876-1931)|title= Biografisch Woordenboek van Nederland|volume=3|location=Den Haag|year=1989|first=H. A.|last=Wage}}</ref>), and read voraciously; the [[Tachtigers]] influenced him greatly, and he became a neo-Romantic of sorts. In addition, he got more critical of his family's Protestantism, but while he would become anti-church, he never became irreligious. In this time period he became friends with [[Carel Adama van Scheltema]] and with painter [[Jan Vogelaar]], who soon became a mentor to Van der Leeuw.<ref name=schipper/>\n\nHe studied law at the [[Universiteit van Amsterdam]] for practical purposes; his parents' financial situation was a concern to him, and law offered good social prospects. This proved motivation enough, and he graduated on time, in 1902, and then worked briefly at the city archives of Delft.<ref name=schipper/> In 1903 he started as ''chef de bureau''<ref name=wage/> at a life insurance company in [[Dordrecht]]. That same year he married his school friend Antonia Johanna Kipp; they had become engaged in 1899. Their marriage remained childless. She is present in many of his early poems and was much interested in mysticism and spirituality; she is credited with shifting Van der Leeuw from skepticism to religiosity,<ref name=schipper/> because of her non-dogmatic though Christian-inflected beliefs.<ref name=wage/>\n\nVan der Leeuw hated his job. He had agreed to take the accountancy exam and had to take classes for that; combined with the full work day he had little time left for creative work. In March of 1907 he resigned his position, on his doctor's advice, for health reasons, but this turned out to be a blessing in disguise: now he was free to pursue his calling. On top of that, his wife's father died, shortly followed by her mother, and he and his wife moved to [[Voorburg]], where he could devote himself to playing the violin, reading, and writing. They lived there until his death at age 54.<ref name=schipper>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]]|accessdate=2 January 2019|url=https://www.digibron.nl/search/detail/012e9d1b05d4aa4e283fc4b2/aart-van-der-leeuw-bescheiden-speelman|language=nl|date=16 April 1981|title= Aart van der Leeuw, bescheiden speelman: Neo-romanticus was lichamelijk zwak, maar geestelijk sterk|first=J.|last=Schipper}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1931 he fell ill with [[pneumonia]] and [[pleurisy]], and never recovered. He died on 17 April, and was buried in Voorburg, with a modest ceremony. A family member read his poem \"Mijn vaders tuinen\" at the gravesite.<ref name=schipper/>\n\n== Work==\nThe novella ''Sint-Veit'' was his literary debut; published in 1908 in [[Albert Verwey]]'s magazine ''De Beweging'', it had been written years before, in Dordrecht. He published also in ''[[De Gids]]'' and ''[[De Nieuwe Gids]]'', but was less interested in the naturalist writers than he was in those of a more symbolist quality. Van der Leeuw began publishing poetry in 1909 and until 1926 published four collections. He also published three collections of short stories, four prose fiction books, critical prose, and some translations. Very much isolated in Voorburg and loath to mingle in the literary world, his friend Van Schendel helped him prepare a number of his books for publication, including ''Liederen en Balladen'' (1910), ''Kinderland'' (1913), and ''Herscheppingen'' (1916). He traveled abroad only when his friends gifted him a trip to Italy for his 50th birthday, a trip he credited with prompting him to write ''Ik en mijn speelman'', a typically neo-Romanticist book that thematizes the relationship between beauty and reality (influenced, Van der Leeuw said, by 17th-c spiritual writer and mystic [[Thomas Traherne]]) and chooses beauty over reality. In his next book, ''De kleine Rudolf'' (1930), there is an attempt to reconcile dream and reality, and now reality is accepted, with romanticism being sought in life, not outside of it. In 1928 he was awarded the [[Lucy B. en C.W. van der Hoogtprijs|C.W. van der Hoogtprijs]] by the [[Maatschappij der Nederlandse Letterkunde]] for ''Het aardsche paradijs'' (1927).<ref name=schipper/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Sint Veit'' (1908)\n* ''Liederen en balladen'' (1911)\n* ''Kinderland'' (1914)\n* ''Herscheppingen'' (1916)\n* ''Sint-Veit en andere vertellingen'' (1919)\n* ''De mythe van een jeugd'' (1921)\n* ''Opvluchten'' (1922)\n* ''De gezegenden'' (1923)\n* ''Vluchtige begroetingen'' (1925)\n* ''De zwerftochten van Odysseus'' (1926)\n* ''Het aardsche paradijs'' (1927)\n* ''Ik en mijn speelman'' (1927)\n* ''De kleine Rudolf'' (1930)\n* ''De opdracht'' (1930)\n* ''Verspreid proza'', nagelaten (1932)\n* ''Die van hun leven vertelden'' (1934)\n* ''Vertellingen'' (1935)\n* ''Momenten van schoonheid en bezinning'' (1947)\n* ''Verzamelde gedichten'' (1950)\n* ''De briefwisseling tussen P.N. van Eyck en Aart van der Leeuw'', bezorgd door Piet Delen (1973)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Dutch writers]]\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aart_van_der_Leeuw"}
{"title_page": "Murod Rajabov", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Murod Rajabov\n|image               = \n|caption             = \n|fullname            = Murod Rajabov\n|birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1995|7|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = [[G\u2018uzor]], [[Uzbekistan]]\n|height              = {{Height|m=}}\n|position            = [[Midfielder (association football)|Defensive midfielder]]\n|currentclub         = [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh|Sogdiana Jizzakh]]\n|clubnumber          = TBD\n|youthyears1         = \n|youthclubs1         = \n|years1              = 2015\n|clubs1              = [[FC Shurtan Guzar|Shurtan Guzar]]\n|caps1               = 16\n|goals1              = 2\n|years2              = 2016\u20132017\n|clubs2              = [[FC AGMK|AGMK Olmaliq]]\n|caps2               = 5\n|goals2              = 0\n|years3              = 2016\n|clubs3              = \u2192 [[FK Novi Pazar|Novi Pazar]] (loan)\n|caps3               = 3\n|goals3              = 0\n|years4              = 2017\n|clubs4              = [[PFC Navbahor Namangan|Navbahor Namangan]]\n|caps4               = 3\n|goals4              = 0\n|years5              = 2018\n|clubs5              = Nurafshon Tashkent\n|caps5               = \n|goals5              = \n|years6              = 2019\u2013\n|clubs6              = [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh|Sogdiana Jizzakh]]\n|caps6               = 1\n|goals6              = 0\n|nationalyears1      = \n|nationalteam1       = \n|nationalcaps1       = \n|nationalgoals1      = \n|club-update         = 16 June 2019\n|nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Murod Rajabov''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0434 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0432}}, born 5 July 1995) is an [[Uzbeks|Uzbek]] [[Association football|footballer]] playing with [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh]] in the [[Uzbek League]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[G\u2018uzor]],<ref>[http://footballfacts.ru/players/1733606-radzhabov-murod Murod Radzhabov] at footballfacts.ru {{in lang|ru}}</ref> Rajabov played with [[FC Shurtan Guzar]] in the [[2015 Uzbek League]], and with [[FC AGMK|AGMK Olmaliq]] in the first half of the [[2016 Uzbek League]].<ref name=\"soccerway\">[https://int.soccerway.com/players/murod-rajabov/399900/ Murod Rajabov profile] at Soccerway</ref>\n\nIn summer 2016, he moved abroad and signed a loan with Serbian top-tier side [[FK Novi Pazar]].<ref>[http://www.fudbal.info/vesti/sest-pojacanja-za-bolju-sezonu-n-pazara/ \u0160est poja\u010danja za bolju sezonu N.Pazara (\"Six signings for a better season for Novi Pazar\")] at fudbal.info, retrieved 23-10-2016 {{in lang|sr}}</ref> He made 3 appearances in the [[2016\u201317 Serbian SuperLiga]] and during winter-break he returned to his former club, [[Olmaliq FK]].<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n\nUpon returning, he played on loan with [[PFC Navbahor Namangan]] in the [[2017 Uzbek League]]. At the end of the season he returned to [[FC AGMK|AGMK Olmaliq]] and was released, signing right next with FC Nurafshon Tashkent and helping the team to finish runner-up of the Uzbekistan Pro League B. He called the attention of top-league side [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh]] that brought him to their squad for the [[2019 Uzbekistan Super League]].<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n\n==International career==\nHe was called for the [[Uzbekistan national under-23 football team|Uzbekistani Olympic team]] training camp that took place from 11 to 16 July 2015.<ref>[http://news.uzreport.uz/news_10_e_132981.html Olympic football team of Uzbekistan to hold a gathering in Tashkent] at news.uzreport.uz, 8-7-2015, retrieved 23-10-2016</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n;Shurtan Guzar\n*UzPFL Cup: 2015<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajabov, Murod}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani footballers]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:FC Shurtan Guzar players]]\n[[Category:FC AGMK players]]\n[[Category:Navbahor Namangan players\u200e]]\n[[Category:FC Sogdiana Jizzakh players]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistan Super League players]]\n[[Category:FK Novi Pazar players]]\n[[Category:Serbian SuperLiga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani expatriate sportspeople in Serbia]]\n\n\n{{Uzbekistan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Murod Rajabov\n|image               = \n|caption             = \n|fullname            = Murod Rajabov\n|birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1995|7|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = [[G\u2018uzor]], [[Uzbekistan]]\n|height              = {{Height|m=}}\n|position            = [[Midfielder (association football)|Defensive midfielder]]\n|currentclub         = [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh|Sogdiana Jizzakh]]\n|clubnumber          = TBD\n|youthyears1         = \n|youthclubs1         = \n|years1              = 2015\n|clubs1              = [[FC Shurtan Guzar|Shurtan Guzar]]\n|caps1               = 16\n|goals1              = 2\n|years2              = 2016\u20132017\n|clubs2              = [[FC AGMK|AGMK Olmaliq]]\n|caps2               = 5\n|goals2              = 0\n|years3              = 2016\n|clubs3              = \u2192 [[FK Novi Pazar|Novi Pazar]] (loan)\n|caps3               = 3\n|goals3              = 0\n|years4              = 2017\n|clubs4              = [[PFC Navbahor Namangan|Navbahor Namangan]]\n|caps4               = 3\n|goals4              = 0\n|years5              = 2018\n|clubs5              = Nurafshon Tashkent\n|caps5               = \n|goals5              = \n|years6              = 2019\u2013\n|clubs6              = [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh|Sogdiana Jizzakh]]\n|caps6               = 1\n|goals6              = 0\n|nationalyears1      = \n|nationalteam1       = \n|nationalcaps1       = \n|nationalgoals1      = \n|club-update         = 16 June 2019\n|nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Murod Rajabov''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0434 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0432}}, born 5 July 1995) is an [[Uzbeks|Uzbek]] [[Association football|footballer]] playing with [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh]] in the [[Uzbek League]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[G\u2018uzor]],<ref>[http://footballfacts.ru/players/1733606-radzhabov-murod Murod Radzhabov] at footballfacts.ru {{in lang|ru}}</ref> Rajabov played with [[FC Shurtan Guzar]] in the [[2015 Uzbek League]], and with [[FC AGMK|AGMK Olmaliq]] in the first half of the [[2016 Uzbek League]].<ref name=\"soccerway\">[https://int.soccerway.com/players/murod-rajabov/399900/ Murod Rajabov profile] at Soccerway</ref>\n\nIn summer 2016, he moved abroad and signed a loan with Serbian top-tier side [[FK Novi Pazar]].<ref>[http://www.fudbal.info/vesti/sest-pojacanja-za-bolju-sezonu-n-pazara/ \u0160est poja\u010danja za bolju sezonu N.Pazara (\"Six signings for a better season for Novi Pazar\")] at fudbal.info, retrieved 23-10-2016 {{in lang|sr}}</ref> He made 3 appearances in the [[2016\u201317 Serbian SuperLiga]] and during winter-break he returned to his former club, [[Olmaliq FK]].<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n\nUpon returning, he played on loan with [[PFC Navbahor Namangan]] in the [[2017 Uzbek League]]. At the end of the season he returned to [[FC AGMK|AGMK Olmaliq]] and was released, signing right next with FC Nurafshon Tashkent and helping the team to finish runner-up of the Uzbekistan Pro League B. He called the attention of top-league side [[FC Sogdiana Jizzakh]] that brought him to their squad for the [[2019 Uzbek League]].<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n\n==International career==\nHe was called for the [[Uzbekistan national under-23 football team|Uzbekistani Olympic team]] training camp that took place from 11 to 16 July 2015.<ref>[http://news.uzreport.uz/news_10_e_132981.html Olympic football team of Uzbekistan to hold a gathering in Tashkent] at news.uzreport.uz, 8-7-2015, retrieved 23-10-2016</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n;Shurtan Guzar\n*UzPFL Cup: 2015<ref name=\"soccerway\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajabov, Murod}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani footballers]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:FC Shurtan Guzar players]]\n[[Category:FC AGMK players]]\n[[Category:Navbahor Namangan players\u200e]]\n[[Category:FC Sogdiana Jizzakh players]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistan Super League players]]\n[[Category:FK Novi Pazar players]]\n[[Category:Serbian SuperLiga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani expatriate sportspeople in Serbia]]\n\n\n{{Uzbekistan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "FkpCascais", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClub career:wl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murod_Rajabov"}
{"title_page": "Aaron Smith (magician)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Aaron K Smith\n| image          = Aaron_Smith_2012.jpg\n| image_size     = 200px\n| caption  = Aaron K Smith in 2012\n| residence   = [[Oklahoma]]\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1976|12|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place =  US\n| occupation  =  Writer, [[Magic (Illusion)|inventor]]\n| spouse      =  \n| children    =  \n| website     =  [http://www.mrgadfly.com MRGADFLY.com]\n| height      = 5'7\"\n}}\n\n'''Aaron Smith''' (born 1976) is an American writer, illustrator, and inventor of magic tricks.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Vanish Magazine|date=August\u2013September 2013|issue=9|page=17}}</ref>\n\n==Mr. Gadfly Magazine==\nAaron Smith was the creator and managing editor of ''Mr. Gadfly'', Journal for Card Magicians, from 2001 to 2002.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Mrgadfly|date=May 2001|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Mrgadfly|date=December 2001|volume=1|issue=5|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MagicPedia|url=http://www.geniimagazine.com/magicpedia/Mr._Gadfly|publisher=Genii Magazine|accessdate=January 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=WorldCat|publisher=WorldCat|oclc=48246936}}</ref> ''Mr. Gadfly'' gained notoriety among magicians as the first magic magazine with a forum devoted solely to its content, wherein readers could communicate directly with the magazine's columnists. ''Mr. Gadfly'' was also the first magic magazine published in both electronic and print formats. Magicians subscribed to the print edition and received the electronic issues free.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Mrgadfly|date=May 2001|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1}}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\nAaron Smith is the founder of The Magic Depot,<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Magic Magazine|date=February 2007|volume=16|issue=6|page=56}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Magic Depot \u2013 Meet The Depot Family|url=http://www.themagicdepot.com/aboutus.php|publisher=The Magic Depot|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Directnic Whois|url=https://directnic.com/whois|publisher=Directnic|accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> a magic trick retailer in Oklahoma, and Gadfly Magic,<ref>{{cite web|title=Directnic Whois|url=https://directnic.com/whois|publisher=Directnic|accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> the production company for his more than one-hundred products currently distributed to magicians worldwide. Much of his earlier work is now out of print.\n\n==Magic Broadcast==\nThough a silent partner at the time, along with Gerald Kirchner and Ryan Pilling, in 2004 Aaron Smith founded the now defunct Magic Broadcast. Magic Broadcast was the first radio station devoted solely to magic. The station quickly grew to six satellite offices operating in three countries, the U.S., Canada, and the U. K.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Magic Magazine|year=2006|volume=15|issue=6|pages=54}}</ref>\n\n==Magic Products ==\nSome of Aaron Smith's magic productions include Mind Leaper (1999), Silk Through Card (1992), Behold the Scarabaeus (2006), Poor Boy ZipTie Escape (2009), STAT Bloody Tongue Skewer (2010), Mental Marker Special FX Pen (2010) and Mental Marker FX Juice (2012), Borrowed & Tied (2011), Flight of the Bubble Gum (2011), Wand Scrolls (2012), Flight Force Five (2012), Poor Boy Billet Knife (2008), and the Old World Siberian Chain Escape (2013) and Ankle Chain Quick-Connect (2013). Aaron Smith introduced the Wizard PK Ring to the U.S. magic community in 2006 on behalf of its inventors.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Magic Magazine|date=March 2006|volume=15|issue=7}}</ref> He also negotiated permission for the term \"PK\" from Magic City, who became the first U. S. magic jobber for the Wizard PK Ring and Vortex PK Ring product lines.<ref>{{cite book|title=PK Ring Owner's Manual|year=2007|publisher=Magic City|page=1}}</ref>\n\n==Author==\n\n The crime thriller, \"No Family For Cannibals - Episode One,\" was released in July 2014 as part of 412C Season One, under the name Aaron K Smith. ({{ISBN|9781310272745}})<ref>{{cite web|title=Aaron Smith Writes Cannibal Thriller|url=http://www.vanishlive.com/2014/07/09/aaron-smith-writes-cannibal-thriller/|publisher=VanishLive|accessdate=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714195552/http://www.vanishlive.com/2014/07/09/aaron-smith-writes-cannibal-thriller/|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=412C|url=http://412c.com|website=412c.com|publisher=412C|accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n<!-- Just press the \"Save page\" button below without changing anything! Doing so will submit your article submission for review. Once you have saved this page you will find a new yellow 'Review waiting' box at the bottom of your submission page. If you have submitted your page previously, either the old pink 'Submission declined' template or the old grey 'Draft' template will still appear at the top of your submission page, but you should ignore it. Again, please don't change anything in this text box. Just press the \"Save page\" button below. -->\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.mrgadfly.com Official blog]\n*[http://www.themagicdepot.com The Magic Depot]\n*[http://www.gadflymagic.com Gadfly Magic (production Company)]\n*[http://www.412c.com No Family For Cannibals (crime thriller)]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of magicians]]\n*[[The Magic Circle (organisation)|The Magic Circle]]\n*[[The Magic Castle]]\n*[[Society of American Magicians]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Aaron K}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American magicians]]\n[[Category:People from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American crime fiction writers|Thrillers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:21st-century American inventors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Aaron K Smith\n| image          = Aaron_Smith_2012.jpg\n| image_size     = 200px\n| caption  = Aaron K Smith in 2012\n| residence   = [[Oklahoma]]\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1976|12|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place =  US\n| occupation  =  Writer, [[Magic (Illusion)|inventor]]\n| spouse      =  \n| children    =  \n| website     =  [http://www.mrgadfly.com MRGADFLY.com]\n| height      = 5'7\"\n}}\n\n'''Aaron Smith''' (born 1976) is an American writer, illustrator, and inventor of magic tricks.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Vanish Magazine|date=August\u2013September 2013|issue=9|page=17}}</ref>\n\n==Mr. Gadfly Magazine==\nAaron Smith was the creator and managing editor of ''Mr. Gadfly'', Journal for Card Magicians, from 2001 to 2002.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Mrgadfly|date=May 2001|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Mrgadfly|date=December 2001|volume=1|issue=5|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MagicPedia|url=http://www.geniimagazine.com/magicpedia/Mr._Gadfly|publisher=Genii Magazine|accessdate=January 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=WorldCat|publisher=WorldCat|oclc=48246936}}</ref> ''Mr. Gadfly'' gained notoriety among magicians as the first magic magazine with a forum devoted solely to its content, wherein readers could communicate directly with the magazine's columnists. ''Mr. Gadfly'' was also the first magic magazine published in both electronic and print formats. Magicians subscribed to the print edition and received the electronic issues free.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Mrgadfly|date=May 2001|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1}}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\nAaron Smith is the founder of The Magic Depot,<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Magic Magazine|date=February 2007|volume=16|issue=6|page=56}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Magic Depot \u2013 Meet The Depot Family|url=http://www.themagicdepot.com/aboutus.php|publisher=The Magic Depot|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Directnic Whois|url=https://directnic.com/whois|publisher=Directnic|accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> a magic trick retailer in Oklahoma, and Gadfly Magic,<ref>{{cite web|title=Directnic Whois|url=https://directnic.com/whois|publisher=Directnic|accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> the production company for his more than one-hundred products currently distributed to magicians worldwide. Much of his earlier work is now out of print.\n\n==Magic Broadcast==\nThough a silent partner at the time, along with Gerald Kirchner and Ryan Pilling, in 2004 Aaron Smith founded the now defunct Magic Broadcast. Magic Broadcast was the first radio station devoted solely to magic. The station quickly grew to six satellite offices operating in three countries, the U.S., Canada, and the U. K.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Magic Magazine|year=2006|volume=15|issue=6|pages=54}}</ref>\n\n==Magic Products ==\nSome of Aaron Smith's magic productions include Mind Leaper (1999), Silk Through Card (1992), Behold the Scarabaeus (2006), Poor Boy ZipTie Escape (2009), STAT Bloody Tongue Skewer (2010), Mental Marker Special FX Pen (2010) and Mental Marker FX Juice (2012), Borrowed & Tied (2011), Flight of the Bubble Gum (2011), Wand Scrolls (2012), Flight Force Five (2012), Poor Boy Billet Knife (2008), and the Old World Siberian Chain Escape (2013) and Ankle Chain Quick-Connect (2013). Aaron Smith introduced the Wizard PK Ring to the U.S. magic community in 2006 on behalf of its inventors.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Magic Magazine|date=March 2006|volume=15|issue=7}}</ref> He also negotiated permission for the term \"PK\" from Magic City, who became the first U. S. magic jobber for the Wizard PK Ring and Vortex PK Ring product lines.<ref>{{cite book|title=PK Ring Owner's Manual|year=2007|publisher=Magic City|page=1}}</ref>\n\n==Author==\n\n The crime thriller, \"No Family For Cannibals - Episode One,\" was released in July 2014 as part of 412C Season One, under the name Aaron K Smith. ({{ISBN|9781310272745}})<ref>{{cite web|title=Aaron Smith Writes Cannibal Thriller|url=http://www.vanishlive.com/2014/07/09/aaron-smith-writes-cannibal-thriller/|publisher=VanishLive|accessdate=9 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714195552/http://www.vanishlive.com/2014/07/09/aaron-smith-writes-cannibal-thriller/|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=412C|url=http://412c.com|website=412c.com|publisher=412C|accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n<!-- Just press the \"Save page\" button below without changing anything! Doing so will submit your article submission for review. Once you have saved this page you will find a new yellow 'Review waiting' box at the bottom of your submission page. If you have submitted your page previously, either the old pink 'Submission declined' template or the old grey 'Draft' template will still appear at the top of your submission page, but you should ignore it. Again, please don't change anything in this text box. Just press the \"Save page\" button below. -->\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.mrgadfly.com Official blog]\n*[http://www.themagicdepot.com The Magic Depot]\n*[http://www.gadflymagic.com Gadfly Magic (production Company)]\n*[http://www.412c.com No Family For Cannibals (crime thriller)]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of magicians]]\n*[[The Magic Circle (organisation)|The Magic Circle]]\n*[[The Magic Castle]]\n*[[Society of American Magicians]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Aaron K}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American magicians]]\n[[Category:People from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American crime fiction writers|Thrillers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:21st-century American inventors]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u20